liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Emilie Gramenz in Washington DC Meanwhile, in a separate case, a federal judge has ruled the writer E Jean Carroll can pursue Donald Trump for more damages, after her successful defamation case against him. Last month a jury found Trump liable for sexually abusing Carroll in the 1990s and later defaming her by lying about it. He was ordered to pay her US $5million (AUS $7.5million). A Manhattan judge has now said Carroll can amend her original lawsuit to include comments Trump made in a CNN town after the verdict - which allows her to seek additional damages. In the town hall, Trump reiterated his criticism of Carroll. He’s also appearing the jury’s verdict.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: More bad news for Trump today

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: By North America bureau chief Jade Macmillan in Washington DC President Joe Biden has rejected Donald Trump’s claims that the case against him is politically motivated, with White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre seeking to reinforce that message again today. “I’m just not going to comment on anything that’s related to the indictment,” she says. "We’re just going to be very mindful here and respect the Department of Justice, let them do their job.” Biden has previously insisted that he had never sought to influence the DOJ, and his Attorney General appointed special counsel Jack Smith to try to keep Mr Trump’s case at arms length. But that won’t stop the former president and his supporters from characterising the investigation as a witch hunt and an attempt to interfere in the 2024 election. Trump is still considered the leading candidate for the Republican presidential nomination, while Biden has declared that he’s also running for office again.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The White House has sought to distance itself from the case

children.content: By North America bureau chief Jade Macmillan in Washington DC

President Joe Biden has rejected Donald Trump’s claims that the case against him is politically motivated, with White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre seeking to reinforce that message again today.
“I’m just not going to comment on anything that’s related to the indictment,” she says.
"We’re just going to be very mindful here and respect the Department of Justice, let them do their job.”
Biden has previously insisted that he had never sought to influence the DOJ, and his Attorney General appointed special counsel Jack Smith to try to keep Mr Trump’s case at arms length.
But that won’t stop the former president and his supporters from characterising the investigation as a witch hunt and an attempt to interfere in the 2024 election.
Trump is still considered the leading candidate for the Republican presidential nomination, while Biden has declared that he’s also running for office again.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Transgender advocate Rose Montoya is no longer welcome at White House events after posting on social media a video of herself going topless for a time at Saturday's Pride Month celebration on the South Lawn. "The behavior was simply unacceptable," White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre says. "It was unfair to the hundreds of attendees who were there to celebrate their families." US President Joe Biden hosted the event to show the administration's support of the LGBTQ+ community. Montoya has defended her post on Instagram and Twitter, saying that "going topless in Washington, DC is legal and I fully support the movement in freeing the nipple". She says critics of her toplessness affirms that she is, in fact, a woman, as a man would not face similar pushback. She says she had "zero intention of trying to be vulgar or be profane in anyway", adding that she covered her nipples with her hands in the video "just to play it safe". Montoya says she will be making a public statement on the situation "soon".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: White House bans transgender advocate who went topless at Biden event

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Crisis support centres will remain open in the New South Wales Hunter Valley region for the next week, in the wake of Sunday night's bus crash which claimed 10 lives. Drop-in clinics will be open from: 9am at the Singleton Youth Venue 10am at the Branxton Community Centre The identities of the victims have become publicly known, with most of them from the Singleton area. NSW Premier Chris Minns will return to the region this morning and is expected to announce further support for those impacted by the tragedy. Emergency service personel are also coming to terms with what they witnessed. The bus driver, Brett Button, faced court yesterday on dangerous and negligent driving charges, and was granted bail .
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Crisis centres open as community comes to grips with deadly bus crash

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Nick Kyrgios has lost on his comeback from knee surgery 7-5, 6-3 to Chinese player Wu Yibing in the first round of the Stuttgart Open. Kyrgios, a 2022 Wimbledon finalist and two-time semifinalist in Stuttgart, was playing for the first time since October in Tokyo. The 28-year-old Australian had a knee operation in January. On Twitter, Kyrgios wrote: "Be patient with me my fans please…. It’s a process to get back to where I was. "I know it’s hard for you to see me perform like today, but I need more time and hopefully can get back to where I was." Wu, who was playing his first professional match on grass, next faces Marton Fucsovics, who rallied to beat Denis Shapovalov 3-6, 6-3, 6-4.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'Be patient with me': Nick Kyrgios loses comeback match after knee surgery

props.alt: Composite of two photos: Australian tennis player Nick Kyrgios hits a ball, and China's Wu Yibing clenches his fist
